## Specification

### 1. Objective

**Problem:** Canton Network lacks shared wallet infrastructure. Every application builder must independently solve:

- User authentication (social login, institutional SSO)
- Private key generation, storage, and management
- Canton Ledger API integration for wallet operations
- CIP-0103 wallet standard compliance
- CIP-0104 traffic observability instrumentation
- Transaction signing UX and policy management
- Wallet recovery mechanisms
- Compliance and audit logging for institutional users

This duplication delays time-to-market by 3–6 months per team, fragments the ecosystem with incompatible wallet implementations, and prevents cross-application wallet portability — a foundational feature that EVM ecosystems take for granted.

**Intended Outcome:** Deliver a modular SDK suite (`@partylayer/enterprise-*`) with an Open Core licensing model. The core SDK modules — authentication, wallet abstraction, Canton Ledger API integration, and UI components — will be open-source (Apache 2.0), serving as the reference implementation of CIP-0103 and the first production tool to generate CIP-0104 traffic metrics. Enterprise backend services (managed signing service, admin dashboard, advanced analytics, premium SSO connectors) will be commercially licensed, ensuring sustainable development beyond the grant period.

The initial release uses a server-side custodial signing architecture, with an upgrade path to MPC threshold signatures in a future proposal once the core SDK and ecosystem adoption are established.

